WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.407 --> 00:00:06.990
PRASAD SETTY: Good
afternoon everyone.

00:00:06.990 --> 00:00:09.990
Welcome to our Talks at
Google session today.

00:00:09.990 --> 00:00:13.180
We are very fortunate to
have a guest amidst us

00:00:13.180 --> 00:00:16.470
who doesn't need
any introduction.

00:00:16.470 --> 00:00:18.462
Seriously, how many people
need an introduction

00:00:18.462 --> 00:00:19.295
to Malcolm Gladwell?

00:00:19.295 --> 00:00:21.080
[LAUGHTER]

00:00:21.080 --> 00:00:23.080
PRASAD SETTY: Malcolm was
the bestselling author

00:00:23.080 --> 00:00:26.330
of "The Tipping Point,"
"Blink," "Outliers," et cetera.

00:00:26.330 --> 00:00:27.960
He's received many honors.

00:00:27.960 --> 00:00:31.160
But I think what he's
probably proudest

00:00:31.160 --> 00:00:34.900
of having accomplished in his
life must be the fact that he

00:00:34.900 --> 00:00:40.130
was our very first Authors
at speaker way back in 2006.

00:00:40.130 --> 00:00:45.560
And so that has started
author's tradition

00:00:45.560 --> 00:00:48.800
where we now have had more
than 1,000 speakers come over

00:00:48.800 --> 00:00:51.910
to Google and share
with us their ideas.

00:00:51.910 --> 00:00:54.260
Malcolm has recently
written a new book

00:00:54.260 --> 00:00:55.520
called "David and Goliath."

00:00:55.520 --> 00:00:58.870
And that is what we'll
be talking about today.

00:00:58.870 --> 00:01:00.870
The format for this,
as you can guess,

00:01:00.870 --> 00:01:02.490
is more of a fireside chat.

00:01:02.490 --> 00:01:06.764
I have a set of questions that
many colleagues have shared

00:01:06.764 --> 00:01:08.930
with me, things that they'd
be interested in hearing

00:01:08.930 --> 00:01:10.355
Malcolm's perspectives on.

00:01:10.355 --> 00:01:13.490
But we'll certainly open it up
for a Q&amp;A with all of you folks

00:01:13.490 --> 00:01:14.070
too.

00:01:14.070 --> 00:01:15.890
And so there are mikes.

00:01:15.890 --> 00:01:19.670
And when it's time, I'll ask
you to line up out there.

00:01:19.670 --> 00:01:21.510
And then we do have
certainly books

00:01:21.510 --> 00:01:24.820
to pass around of
"David and Goliath."

00:01:24.820 --> 00:01:29.330
So let's give a very warm round
of welcome to Malcolm Gladwell.

00:01:29.330 --> 00:01:35.895
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:35.895 --> 00:01:38.410
PRASAD SETTY: Malcolm,
just to kick this off,

00:01:38.410 --> 00:01:40.990
what would you like to
tell us about this new book

00:01:40.990 --> 00:01:45.440
and why you chose to write it?

00:01:45.440 --> 00:01:47.440
MALCOLM GLADWELL: Well,
it's a book called

00:01:47.440 --> 00:01:48.300
"David and Goliath."

00:01:48.300 --> 00:01:50.280
And it's about
underdogs, misfits,

00:01:50.280 --> 00:01:53.000
and the art of battling giants.

00:01:53.000 --> 00:01:54.920
It's about a number of things.

00:01:54.920 --> 00:02:00.020
But it's principally about
asymmetrical conflicts

00:02:00.020 --> 00:02:06.690
and the strategies that are
available to the weaker side.

00:02:06.690 --> 00:02:10.020
And then sort of
secondarily it's

00:02:10.020 --> 00:02:15.910
about the accuracy of our
assumptions about advantages

00:02:15.910 --> 00:02:19.170
and the nature of advantages
and disadvantages.

00:02:19.170 --> 00:02:24.700
So is our perception in an
asymmetrical conflict of one

00:02:24.700 --> 00:02:28.330
side is the favorite and the
other side as the underdog

00:02:28.330 --> 00:02:31.080
accurate?

00:02:31.080 --> 00:02:34.310
Or is it an illusion based
on our own faulty assumptions

00:02:34.310 --> 00:02:35.990
about the nature of advantage?

00:02:35.990 --> 00:02:39.100
And then the third
argument in the book

00:02:39.100 --> 00:02:43.360
has to do with
whether adversity is

00:02:43.360 --> 00:02:47.690
a more useful way of learning
certain kinds of lessons

00:02:47.690 --> 00:02:54.260
than conditions
without constraint.

00:02:54.260 --> 00:02:56.477
So it's called
"David and Goliath"

00:02:56.477 --> 00:02:58.060
because the story
of David and Goliath

00:02:58.060 --> 00:02:59.910
is in fact a
perfect illustration

00:02:59.910 --> 00:03:00.720
of this very thing.

00:03:03.420 --> 00:03:06.220
David's choice of
weapon, the sling,

00:03:06.220 --> 00:03:08.120
is actually an incredibly
devastating weapon.

00:03:10.750 --> 00:03:13.730
You place a rock
in a leather pouch,

00:03:13.730 --> 00:03:16.280
and you swing it around
at roughly six or seven

00:03:16.280 --> 00:03:18.330
revolutions per second.

00:03:18.330 --> 00:03:20.780
You release one of the chords.

00:03:20.780 --> 00:03:24.310
The rock goes forward
at speeds, depending

00:03:24.310 --> 00:03:26.130
on the weight of
the rock, speeds

00:03:26.130 --> 00:03:31.120
of probably 30
meters per second.

00:03:31.120 --> 00:03:36.080
The stopping power of a typical
projectile launched in that way

00:03:36.080 --> 00:03:41.570
is the equivalent of
a 45 caliber handgun.

00:03:41.570 --> 00:03:45.480
And the accuracy of people
in those years with one

00:03:45.480 --> 00:03:47.470
of these things
was extraordinary.

00:03:47.470 --> 00:03:54.700
We know from primitive
tries that somebody

00:03:54.700 --> 00:03:58.770
with a couple of
years of experience

00:03:58.770 --> 00:04:00.690
could hit the
center of that clock

00:04:00.690 --> 00:04:03.270
very easily from
where I'm standing.

00:04:03.270 --> 00:04:08.990
So David up against Goliath
has superior technology.

00:04:08.990 --> 00:04:12.020
Routinely slingers
defeated heavy infantry,

00:04:12.020 --> 00:04:15.490
which is what Goliath is,
in combat in ancient times.

00:04:15.490 --> 00:04:18.399
In fact, ancient
army's had slingers

00:04:18.399 --> 00:04:21.570
on their kind of payroll
for that precise purpose.

00:04:21.570 --> 00:04:24.840
The minute he
takes out the sling

00:04:24.840 --> 00:04:28.520
and it changes the rules of
combat, he is the favorite.

00:04:28.520 --> 00:04:30.300
He's not going to lose, right?

00:04:30.300 --> 00:04:32.130
There's only Goliath,
who's lumbering.

00:04:32.130 --> 00:04:34.088
And then the other
fascinating about that story

00:04:34.088 --> 00:04:38.117
is that Goliath-- there's
been all this speculation

00:04:38.117 --> 00:04:39.700
in the medical
literature about what's

00:04:39.700 --> 00:04:41.320
going on with Goliath
because there's

00:04:41.320 --> 00:04:42.650
all these weird things he does.

00:04:42.650 --> 00:04:44.160
He moves very slowly.

00:04:44.160 --> 00:04:47.300
He's led on to the valley
floor by an attendant.

00:04:47.300 --> 00:04:50.930
And the thinking is that he
has what's called acromegaly,

00:04:50.930 --> 00:04:54.887
which is the condition
caused by a benign tumor

00:04:54.887 --> 00:04:56.970
on your pituitary gland
that causes overproduction

00:04:56.970 --> 00:04:58.660
of human growth hormone.

00:04:58.660 --> 00:04:59.260
He's tall.

00:04:59.260 --> 00:05:00.170
He's a giant.

00:05:00.170 --> 00:05:05.100
Giants are often-- you know,
Andre the Giant had acromegaly.

00:05:05.100 --> 00:05:07.020
We think Abraham
Lincoln had acromegaly.

00:05:07.020 --> 00:05:09.730
When people are unusually tall,
that's one of the explanations.

00:05:09.730 --> 00:05:11.910
And acromegaly
has a side effect,

00:05:11.910 --> 00:05:15.270
which is that it compresses
the optic nerves.

00:05:15.270 --> 00:05:19.740
And people with acromegaly often
have severe vision problems.

00:05:19.740 --> 00:05:22.990
Goliath is probably half
blind, in other words.

00:05:22.990 --> 00:05:26.710
So a guy who's
half blind goes up

00:05:26.710 --> 00:05:30.840
against another guy with an
incredibly lethal weapon,

00:05:30.840 --> 00:05:33.930
accurate to within
a hair's breath

00:05:33.930 --> 00:05:37.370
from 50 yards away and with the
stopping power of 45 pistol.

00:05:37.370 --> 00:05:40.120
And yet for 3,000
years we've insisted

00:05:40.120 --> 00:05:41.800
that guy is an underdog.

00:05:41.800 --> 00:05:44.040
It's insane, right?

00:05:44.040 --> 00:05:47.710
It's the most irrational
reading of the allocation

00:05:47.710 --> 00:05:50.160
of advantages and
disadvantages in that conflict.

00:05:50.160 --> 00:05:53.050
So the question is if we
are so profoundly irrational

00:05:53.050 --> 00:05:58.340
in the way we have read the
relative strengths of the two

00:05:58.340 --> 00:06:00.700
parties in that most
famous of conflicts,

00:06:00.700 --> 00:06:03.960
how many other
situations do we misread?

00:06:03.960 --> 00:06:06.620
And that's what
the book's about.

00:06:06.620 --> 00:06:08.982
And I think the answer is lots.

00:06:08.982 --> 00:06:10.690
PRASAD SETTY: And you
do talk about quite

00:06:10.690 --> 00:06:13.690
a few real underdogs
in the book as well.

00:06:13.690 --> 00:06:17.660
And one of the examples you
were mentioning at lunch today

00:06:17.660 --> 00:06:19.620
was about this girl's
basketball team.

00:06:19.620 --> 00:06:22.009
Tell us about that and
how that was shaped.

00:06:22.009 --> 00:06:24.300
MALCOLM GLADWELL: Well this
is one of the reasons I got

00:06:24.300 --> 00:06:27.150
started writing the book is I
ran into a guy who some of you

00:06:27.150 --> 00:06:32.020
may know, the guy who founded
Tibco, Vivek Ranadive.

00:06:32.020 --> 00:06:36.320
I met him at a conference and
didn't realize who he was.

00:06:36.320 --> 00:06:40.760
Weirdly, by the way, I
had another experience

00:06:40.760 --> 00:06:43.620
in this exact same thing where
I met someone at a conference,

00:06:43.620 --> 00:06:46.060
did not realize who
they were, and just

00:06:46.060 --> 00:06:48.250
had a conversation with
sports as a result.

00:06:48.250 --> 00:06:52.950
The first person I did
this with was Larry Page.

00:06:52.950 --> 00:06:55.520
I met him years
ago, and I thought

00:06:55.520 --> 00:06:57.560
he was just a graduate student.

00:06:57.560 --> 00:06:58.350
And I had no idea.

00:06:58.350 --> 00:07:00.200
And so I was like, where
did you got to school?

00:07:00.200 --> 00:07:01.640
He's like, oh,
I'm from Michigan.

00:07:01.640 --> 00:07:03.120
So we just talked about
Michigan State basketball

00:07:03.120 --> 00:07:03.995
for about 45 minutes.

00:07:03.995 --> 00:07:05.579
And then afterwards,
people were like,

00:07:05.579 --> 00:07:07.078
do you know who you
were talking to?

00:07:07.078 --> 00:07:07.690
I had no clue.

00:07:07.690 --> 00:07:10.750
Anyway, I did the same
thing with this guy, Vivek.

00:07:10.750 --> 00:07:12.610
So he started
telling me about how

00:07:12.610 --> 00:07:16.040
he coached his 12-year-old
daughter's basketball team.

00:07:16.040 --> 00:07:18.950
And because he's Indian, he
had no clue about basketball.

00:07:18.950 --> 00:07:20.480
So he goes to-- I mean--

00:07:20.480 --> 00:07:22.722
[LAUGHTER]

00:07:22.722 --> 00:07:24.180
PRASAD SETTY: I
can relate to that.

00:07:24.180 --> 00:07:24.540
MALCOLM GLADWELL: OK.

00:07:24.540 --> 00:07:25.040
Good.

00:07:25.040 --> 00:07:26.470
Just checking.

00:07:26.470 --> 00:07:28.900
There was no natural
reason to assume

00:07:28.900 --> 00:07:30.790
he would know a lot
about basketball.

00:07:30.790 --> 00:07:31.790
PRASAD SETTY: Underdogs.

00:07:31.790 --> 00:07:32.340
[LAUGHTER]

00:07:32.340 --> 00:07:35.140
MALCOLM GLADWELL:
That's right, exactly.

00:07:35.140 --> 00:07:37.450
Although, only an India, a
country of a billion people,

00:07:37.450 --> 00:07:40.700
could claim to be an underdog.

00:07:40.700 --> 00:07:44.750
So Vivek goes and studies-- in
his kind of software engineer

00:07:44.750 --> 00:07:46.610
kind of way-- goes to
study basketball games

00:07:46.610 --> 00:07:49.260
and becomes convinced that
Americans are completely

00:07:49.260 --> 00:07:51.230
irrational in the way
they play basketball.

00:07:51.230 --> 00:07:53.370
Because he doesn't
understand why,

00:07:53.370 --> 00:07:56.060
if you are the weaker
party in a game,

00:07:56.060 --> 00:07:59.930
you don't do the full
court press all the time.

00:07:59.930 --> 00:08:02.340
Because you're going to
lose otherwise, right?

00:08:02.340 --> 00:08:04.220
And by not playing
the full court press,

00:08:04.220 --> 00:08:07.530
you are allowing your opponent
to do precisely the thing

00:08:07.530 --> 00:08:10.300
that your opponent
excels at, which

00:08:10.300 --> 00:08:15.850
is to pass and dribble and
execute choreographed plays.

00:08:15.850 --> 00:08:28.450
Why would you give them
the easiest possible route

00:08:28.450 --> 00:08:31.310
to doing the thing that
makes them better than you?

00:08:31.310 --> 00:08:33.280
So he says your only
hope is to slow them down

00:08:33.280 --> 00:08:36.990
and to defeat them at the things
they're not expert at, ie,

00:08:36.990 --> 00:08:38.570
play the full court press.

00:08:38.570 --> 00:08:40.513
If it fails, so what?

00:08:40.513 --> 00:08:41.679
You're going to lose anyway.

00:08:41.679 --> 00:08:43.690
But at least you've
raised your chances

00:08:43.690 --> 00:08:49.915
of losing from 95% to
something less than 95%.

00:08:53.900 --> 00:08:57.020
This is relevant to him because
his daughter's team is utterly

00:08:57.020 --> 00:08:58.380
without any talent whatsoever.

00:08:58.380 --> 00:09:04.060
These are the very, very,
very skinny, somewhat nerdy

00:09:04.060 --> 00:09:07.710
daughters of programmers
from Silicon Valley.

00:09:07.710 --> 00:09:09.414
[LAUGHTER]

00:09:09.414 --> 00:09:10.830
MALCOLM GLADWELL:
So he does this.

00:09:10.830 --> 00:09:13.590
And his strategy
is we're not going

00:09:13.590 --> 00:09:18.720
to learn how to shoot,
dribble, or pass.

00:09:18.720 --> 00:09:21.330
We're not even going to practice
any kind of offensive plays.

00:09:21.330 --> 00:09:22.830
What you're going
to do is I'm going

00:09:22.830 --> 00:09:24.496
to get you in really,
really good shape.

00:09:24.496 --> 00:09:27.530
And I'm going to teach you to
do this for the entire game.

00:09:27.530 --> 00:09:31.310
And what happens is that if
you do this for the entire game

00:09:31.310 --> 00:09:34.280
in a basketball game made
up of 12-year-old girls,

00:09:34.280 --> 00:09:38.170
the other team will not advance
the ball past mid court.

00:09:38.170 --> 00:09:40.180
And so Vivek's
team starts to win

00:09:40.180 --> 00:09:42.627
by scores like eight, nothing.

00:09:42.627 --> 00:09:43.664
[LAUGHTER]

00:09:43.664 --> 00:09:45.080
MALCOLM GLADWELL:
And they advance

00:09:45.080 --> 00:09:46.329
to the national championships.

00:09:50.050 --> 00:09:51.640
It's such a hilarious story.

00:09:51.640 --> 00:09:58.860
And, of course, the
opponents are so flummoxed

00:09:58.860 --> 00:10:01.250
by this, first of
all, and then outraged

00:10:01.250 --> 00:10:05.230
because the thing that Vivek
is playing with his girls

00:10:05.230 --> 00:10:07.450
is not actually
basketball, right?

00:10:07.450 --> 00:10:12.670
If you don't dribble,
pass, or shoot, and have

00:10:12.670 --> 00:10:15.100
no intention of so
doing, and if the score

00:10:15.100 --> 00:10:18.210
at the end of the game is
something like six, nothing,

00:10:18.210 --> 00:10:19.940
that's not basketball.

00:10:19.940 --> 00:10:22.230
That's another sport.

00:10:22.230 --> 00:10:24.132
And so they throw
chairs on the court.

00:10:24.132 --> 00:10:26.340
They challenge him to fist
fights in the parking lot.

00:10:26.340 --> 00:10:27.790
They scream at the refs.

00:10:27.790 --> 00:10:31.010
And he is sort of
massively different.

00:10:31.010 --> 00:10:34.430
To him this is more of
the strange idiosyncrasies

00:10:34.430 --> 00:10:38.030
of the American
sporting personality.

00:10:38.030 --> 00:10:43.730
And that is a lovely
illustration of my very point

00:10:43.730 --> 00:10:49.050
because why is he compelled
to follow this strategy?

00:10:49.050 --> 00:10:51.570
Because he's got nothing, right?

00:10:51.570 --> 00:10:53.410
He's got bupkis.

00:10:53.410 --> 00:10:56.191
His girls are incapable of
playing the game of basketball,

00:10:56.191 --> 00:10:56.690
right?

00:10:56.690 --> 00:10:57.564
So what does that do?

00:10:57.564 --> 00:11:01.490
It spurs him to find a
completely alternate strategy

00:11:01.490 --> 00:11:02.960
that's far more successful.

00:11:02.960 --> 00:11:05.470
And this is, of course, the
great story of innovation,

00:11:05.470 --> 00:11:05.970
right?

00:11:05.970 --> 00:11:12.370
That nothing acts
ts a greater spur

00:11:12.370 --> 00:11:18.280
to innovation then the
absence of advantage.

00:11:18.280 --> 00:11:21.520
So if that's the case,
there must be situations

00:11:21.520 --> 00:11:26.920
where it is not advantageous
to have advantages, right?

00:11:26.920 --> 00:11:28.800
The only situation
where he's better off

00:11:28.800 --> 00:11:30.904
is if his girls are
really talented.

00:11:30.904 --> 00:11:32.320
So there's a series
of conditions.

00:11:32.320 --> 00:11:36.350
You could have no talent,
you can have massive talent,

00:11:36.350 --> 00:11:38.320
and you can be
anywhere in the middle.

00:11:38.320 --> 00:11:40.670
The only situation
where he could also

00:11:40.670 --> 00:11:42.270
have reached the
national championship

00:11:42.270 --> 00:11:44.610
is in the 99th ninth
percentile condition

00:11:44.610 --> 00:11:46.940
where his team is
massively talented.

00:11:46.940 --> 00:11:49.560
But had he been at
anything other--

00:11:49.560 --> 00:11:51.115
so he's in the 1% condition.

00:11:51.115 --> 00:11:52.740
That's advantageous
because that forces

00:11:52.740 --> 00:11:54.300
you to play the
full court press.

00:11:54.300 --> 00:11:56.870
The 99th percentile
condition is advantageous.

00:11:56.870 --> 00:12:00.080
But the two through
98 is not advantageous

00:12:00.080 --> 00:12:03.790
because you have no
incentive from to two to 98

00:12:03.790 --> 00:12:06.020
to try anything new.

00:12:06.020 --> 00:12:08.170
Your instinct is just
to play the game the way

00:12:08.170 --> 00:12:10.160
the game is supposed
to be played.

00:12:10.160 --> 00:12:12.190
So had his girls been
even a little bit better,

00:12:12.190 --> 00:12:13.398
they would've been worse off.

00:12:15.835 --> 00:12:17.210
PRASAD SETTY: So
you're saying we

00:12:17.210 --> 00:12:18.864
should be as bad as we can be?

00:12:18.864 --> 00:12:20.280
MALCOLM GLADWELL:
Well, I'm saying

00:12:20.280 --> 00:12:27.660
there are situations where being
bad is highly advantageous.

00:12:27.660 --> 00:12:30.650
And I don't go into
this in the book,

00:12:30.650 --> 00:12:33.410
but if you've read
"Innovator's Dilemma," that's

00:12:33.410 --> 00:12:35.690
what "Innovator's Dilemma"
is all about, right?

00:12:35.690 --> 00:12:38.420
The disruptive
outsider is the one

00:12:38.420 --> 00:12:42.410
who is incapable of meeting
the marketplace needs

00:12:42.410 --> 00:12:44.380
as the market is
traditionally defined.

00:12:44.380 --> 00:12:46.280
They can't do it.

00:12:46.280 --> 00:12:47.780
So what they do they do?

00:12:47.780 --> 00:12:50.510
They try a completely
new half-assed approach,

00:12:50.510 --> 00:12:53.040
which in the beginning,
doesn't work.

00:12:53.040 --> 00:12:55.550
But by that very nature of
trying something completely

00:12:55.550 --> 00:12:57.720
outside the
mainstream, they end up

00:12:57.720 --> 00:13:00.730
upending the--
were they any good,

00:13:00.730 --> 00:13:02.910
they would never be
forced to do that.

00:13:02.910 --> 00:13:04.824
So it's the same
kind of principle.

00:13:04.824 --> 00:13:06.490
PRASAD SETTY: One of
the things that you

00:13:06.490 --> 00:13:09.770
talk about in the
book which hinders

00:13:09.770 --> 00:13:12.560
your chance of
improving your success

00:13:12.560 --> 00:13:16.820
is something that you say
that we're all susceptible to.

00:13:16.820 --> 00:13:21.830
And the acronym that you use
is EICD, Elite Institution

00:13:21.830 --> 00:13:23.470
Cognitive Disorder.

00:13:23.470 --> 00:13:25.230
Tell us about that
because that's

00:13:25.230 --> 00:13:28.065
something I'm sure we
don't know anything about.

00:13:28.065 --> 00:13:29.690
MALCOLM GLADWELL: I
gave a talk on this

00:13:29.690 --> 00:13:32.190
at the Google
Zeitgeist Conference.

00:13:32.190 --> 00:13:35.270
And because I was
having fun with it,

00:13:35.270 --> 00:13:37.130
I invented the acronym
for the conference.

00:13:37.130 --> 00:13:39.540
It's not actually in the book.

00:13:39.540 --> 00:13:44.810
Elite Institution Cognitive
Disorder is the mistaken belief

00:13:44.810 --> 00:13:48.440
that attending the most elite
institution you can get into

00:13:48.440 --> 00:13:51.220
is always in your best interest.

00:13:51.220 --> 00:13:52.950
This is false.

00:13:52.950 --> 00:13:54.920
There are a number of
many, many situations

00:13:54.920 --> 00:13:58.030
where it is not in your best
interest to go to, for example,

00:13:58.030 --> 00:13:59.560
the best school
you can get into.

00:13:59.560 --> 00:14:01.520
But rather it's in
your best interest

00:14:01.520 --> 00:14:05.400
to go to, at the very
most, your second choice,

00:14:05.400 --> 00:14:10.130
and probably, ideally, your
third or fourth choice.

00:14:10.130 --> 00:14:11.690
The reason is as follows.

00:14:11.690 --> 00:14:15.180
The best predictor of success
in a highly competitive

00:14:15.180 --> 00:14:19.540
environment like, for example,
law school, or more relevant,

00:14:19.540 --> 00:14:22.200
the one I use in my book
is getting a STEM degree,

00:14:22.200 --> 00:14:25.250
getting a science and math
degree-- science and math

00:14:25.250 --> 00:14:28.280
education at the
university level

00:14:28.280 --> 00:14:32.090
is marked by dropout rates
that are north of 50%.

00:14:32.090 --> 00:14:36.330
Most people who try to get a
science and math agree fail.

00:14:36.330 --> 00:14:40.290
So the question is if you would
like to get a science and math

00:14:40.290 --> 00:14:43.230
degree, what is the
optimal strategy?

00:14:43.230 --> 00:14:45.740
And the optimal
strategy is not to go

00:14:45.740 --> 00:14:47.480
to the best school you get into.

00:14:47.480 --> 00:14:48.150
Why?

00:14:48.150 --> 00:14:50.770
Because the best predictor
of success in getting

00:14:50.770 --> 00:14:53.690
a degree is not your absolute
level of intelligence

00:14:53.690 --> 00:14:56.530
but your relative
level of intelligence.

00:14:56.530 --> 00:14:57.880
It's your class rank.

00:15:02.980 --> 00:15:05.770
It's your rank relative to
your peers in your class,

00:15:05.770 --> 00:15:08.280
not your SAT score or your IQ.

00:15:08.280 --> 00:15:15.380
So basically anyone, if you
fall in the bottom third

00:15:15.380 --> 00:15:20.180
of your class, your
chances of dropping out

00:15:20.180 --> 00:15:22.642
rise astronomically.

00:15:22.642 --> 00:15:24.350
So you should basically
follow a strategy

00:15:24.350 --> 00:15:26.670
that minimizes your
chances of falling

00:15:26.670 --> 00:15:28.090
in the bottom third
of your class.

00:15:28.090 --> 00:15:28.923
What does that mean?

00:15:28.923 --> 00:15:31.810
Don't go to a good
school, right?

00:15:31.810 --> 00:15:35.300
Now what's fascinating
about this,

00:15:35.300 --> 00:15:37.990
the amazing thing
about this, is that we

00:15:37.990 --> 00:15:42.010
appear to have
consistently undervalued

00:15:42.010 --> 00:15:47.370
the psychological
costs of finishing

00:15:47.370 --> 00:15:49.706
in the bottom half of any
competitive situation.

00:15:49.706 --> 00:15:51.080
In other words,
what we overvalue

00:15:51.080 --> 00:15:54.170
is the prestige of
the institution.

00:15:54.170 --> 00:15:56.620
And what we undervalue
is the cost to you

00:15:56.620 --> 00:15:59.470
of not succeeding
at that institution.

00:15:59.470 --> 00:16:01.470
And so there's a
beautiful illustration

00:16:01.470 --> 00:16:05.650
of this in this study that
was done of economics PhDs.

00:16:05.650 --> 00:16:08.630
So what we do is we take
the top 30 PhD Programs

00:16:08.630 --> 00:16:10.360
in economics in America.

00:16:10.360 --> 00:16:13.180
And we break the
students down by how

00:16:13.180 --> 00:16:17.810
they rank in their
graduate class.

00:16:17.810 --> 00:16:21.130
And then we look at
their publication rate

00:16:21.130 --> 00:16:24.600
six years out of
attaining their PhD.

00:16:24.600 --> 00:16:26.780
These are those who
take the academic route.

00:16:26.780 --> 00:16:30.650
So in something like economics,
we use your publication rate

00:16:30.650 --> 00:16:34.640
as the number of
papers you get accepted

00:16:34.640 --> 00:16:35.640
by prestigious journals.

00:16:35.640 --> 00:16:39.310
It's used as a proxy for
your success as an economist.

00:16:39.310 --> 00:16:40.880
What do we find when
we look at that?

00:16:40.880 --> 00:16:44.380
What we find is the
95th percentile student

00:16:44.380 --> 00:16:49.680
at Harvard, Stanford,
Princeton, MIT, et cetera,

00:16:49.680 --> 00:16:52.720
publishes a lot of papers,
as you would expect.

00:16:52.720 --> 00:16:54.110
They're brilliant.

00:16:54.110 --> 00:16:57.560
But the drop off from the
95th to the 80th percent

00:16:57.560 --> 00:16:59.170
is astronomical.

00:16:59.170 --> 00:17:03.240
And by the time you get to
the middle of the PhD class

00:17:03.240 --> 00:17:06.390
at elite schools, they're
not publishing at all.

00:17:06.390 --> 00:17:09.880
In fact, the 95th
percentile student

00:17:09.880 --> 00:17:12.790
at the worst PhD
program you can find

00:17:12.790 --> 00:17:16.319
will publish more and be a
more successful economist then

00:17:16.319 --> 00:17:21.560
the 75th percentile student
at Harvard, MIT, and Stanford.

00:17:21.560 --> 00:17:23.849
Now, there are many
explanations for that.

00:17:23.849 --> 00:17:25.750
But the most
parsimonious explanation

00:17:25.750 --> 00:17:31.500
is it is so traumatic and
humiliating and overwhelming

00:17:31.500 --> 00:17:35.230
to be in an elite program and
see a handful of people just

00:17:35.230 --> 00:17:38.540
beat the crap out of you, but
you are permanently impaired.

00:17:41.260 --> 00:17:43.670
And my message at
Google Zeitgeist

00:17:43.670 --> 00:17:48.010
was that I think
the logical response

00:17:48.010 --> 00:17:50.950
to this line of reasoning
is that you should hire only

00:17:50.950 --> 00:17:52.750
on the basis of
class rank and not

00:17:52.750 --> 00:17:54.850
on the basis of institution.

00:17:54.850 --> 00:17:56.600
In other words, you
should have don't ask,

00:17:56.600 --> 00:18:00.800
don't tell when it comes to
the name of your undergraduate

00:18:00.800 --> 00:18:01.842
and graduate institution.

00:18:01.842 --> 00:18:04.050
We should be indifferent to
where you went to school.

00:18:04.050 --> 00:18:05.500
We should only
care about how you

00:18:05.500 --> 00:18:10.360
ranked because if it's so
devastating to be in anything

00:18:10.360 --> 00:18:12.290
other than the top
third of your class,

00:18:12.290 --> 00:18:16.860
I don't want you if you weren't
in the top third of your class,

00:18:16.860 --> 00:18:17.560
right?

00:18:17.560 --> 00:18:19.600
Now I'm being playful
a little bit here.

00:18:19.600 --> 00:18:23.030
But the point is
do you see how we

00:18:23.030 --> 00:18:25.740
have allocated our strengths?

00:18:25.740 --> 00:18:29.670
And our notion of
what is an advantage

00:18:29.670 --> 00:18:33.420
and what is a disadvantage are
allocated in an irrational way.

00:18:35.990 --> 00:18:39.330
We've become obsessed with
the advantages of prestige.

00:18:39.330 --> 00:18:42.090
We have not paid attention to
the disadvantages of prestige.

00:18:42.090 --> 00:18:45.024
And that's a mistake.

00:18:45.024 --> 00:18:46.440
PRASAD SETTY: But
some people seem

00:18:46.440 --> 00:18:50.040
to get motivated by being
surrounded by people

00:18:50.040 --> 00:18:51.710
smarter than they are, right?

00:18:51.710 --> 00:18:52.632
So that's sort of--

00:18:52.632 --> 00:18:54.590
MALCOLM GLADWELL: Not
economic PhDs apparently.

00:18:54.590 --> 00:18:56.080
[LAUGHTER]

00:18:56.080 --> 00:19:00.200
MALCOLM GLADWELL: No, I mean,
intuitively, I agree with you.

00:19:00.200 --> 00:19:04.870
I want to find reasons to
like elite institutions.

00:19:04.870 --> 00:19:06.771
All my friends went
to elite institutions.

00:19:06.771 --> 00:19:08.270
Should I have
children, I would want

00:19:08.270 --> 00:19:10.220
them to go to
elite institutions.

00:19:10.220 --> 00:19:12.970
But the problem is that when
we go and systematically look

00:19:12.970 --> 00:19:15.430
for those advantages,
we can't find them.

00:19:15.430 --> 00:19:16.680
I don't go into it in my book.

00:19:16.680 --> 00:19:19.700
But there's a long
and rich tradition

00:19:19.700 --> 00:19:23.260
in economics in
which people hunt

00:19:23.260 --> 00:19:26.190
for the value of
an elite education.

00:19:26.190 --> 00:19:29.440
And they can't find it.

00:19:29.440 --> 00:19:34.140
So we know that it is the
case that a student who

00:19:34.140 --> 00:19:38.060
goes to Harvard earns more money
in the course of their career

00:19:38.060 --> 00:19:41.580
than a student who goes to
the University of Tennessee.

00:19:41.580 --> 00:19:42.225
OK.

00:19:42.225 --> 00:19:43.975
But that doesn't tell
you anything at all.

00:19:43.975 --> 00:19:47.720
What you really need to do is to
find two students, both of who

00:19:47.720 --> 00:19:49.794
get into Harvard,
one of whom goes

00:19:49.794 --> 00:19:51.460
and one goes to
University of Tennessee.

00:19:51.460 --> 00:19:53.870
And then compare
their career earnings.

00:19:53.870 --> 00:19:57.960
And when you equalize
for the person,

00:19:57.960 --> 00:19:59.340
you can't find any difference.

00:19:59.340 --> 00:20:02.202
In other words, it's
not that Harvard

00:20:02.202 --> 00:20:03.410
is making you a lot of money.

00:20:03.410 --> 00:20:05.576
It's the kind of person who
gets accepted by Harvard

00:20:05.576 --> 00:20:06.940
makes a lot of money.

00:20:06.940 --> 00:20:10.751
And then there is an even
cleverer line of things.

00:20:10.751 --> 00:20:12.500
There's now been like
ten studies on this,

00:20:12.500 --> 00:20:15.420
and it's so interesting.

00:20:15.420 --> 00:20:18.220
They now look at
elite high schools.

00:20:18.220 --> 00:20:23.070
So what is the benefit of going
to a selective high school?

00:20:23.070 --> 00:20:27.510
Now, intuitively, you would
think it must show up.

00:20:27.510 --> 00:20:31.140
You must be able to see, whether
in test scores, or the quality

00:20:31.140 --> 00:20:32.910
of the college you go
to, or somewhere, we

00:20:32.910 --> 00:20:34.710
must see some impact of that.

00:20:34.710 --> 00:20:39.680
And we can't find advantage.

00:20:42.550 --> 00:20:47.730
Once you do that
equalization thing,

00:20:47.730 --> 00:20:49.630
if you are a smart
kid, in other words,

00:20:49.630 --> 00:20:51.330
it doesn't matter
what school you go to.

00:20:53.930 --> 00:20:58.747
Smart is smart, which is
an intriguing finding.

00:20:58.747 --> 00:20:59.830
PRASAD SETTY: [INAUDIBLE].

00:20:59.830 --> 00:21:01.490
Thank you.

00:21:01.490 --> 00:21:04.250
I want to switch
topics a little bit.

00:21:04.250 --> 00:21:06.030
You know, you do
a remarkable job

00:21:06.030 --> 00:21:08.550
of popularizing social sciences.

00:21:08.550 --> 00:21:12.497
And by the way, I forgot
