00:23:43.646 --> 00:23:46.919
[LAUGHTER]

00:23:46.919 --> 00:23:48.210
PRASAD SETTY: Related question.

00:23:48.210 --> 00:23:53.140
You use a lot of stories to
bring your thoughts to life.

00:23:53.140 --> 00:23:55.770
And the stories add a lot
of emotional richness,

00:23:55.770 --> 00:23:58.620
and we can really
connect with them.

00:23:58.620 --> 00:24:02.800
But how do you ensure that the
stories that you're picking

00:24:02.800 --> 00:24:06.620
are the most representative
of the phenomenon that you're

00:24:06.620 --> 00:24:07.430
trying to describe?

00:24:07.430 --> 00:24:10.300
Because you could
probably find a story

00:24:10.300 --> 00:24:12.390
to fit any theory that
you want, one story.

00:24:15.750 --> 00:24:17.320
MALCOLM GLADWELL: Yeah.

00:24:17.320 --> 00:24:20.350
So there's a whole set
of trade offs here.

00:24:23.340 --> 00:24:27.230
Storytelling, by
definition, has one

00:24:27.230 --> 00:24:30.710
great disadvantage, which
is you are representing

00:24:30.710 --> 00:24:35.620
a single narrative,
a single experience.

00:24:35.620 --> 00:24:39.140
On the other side
of the equation,

00:24:39.140 --> 00:24:41.330
story telling has a
massive advantage,

00:24:41.330 --> 00:24:46.080
which is there is no better way
to communicate and move people

00:24:46.080 --> 00:24:49.080
than through story.

00:24:49.080 --> 00:24:52.020
So what I've always tried
to do is-- the reason

00:24:52.020 --> 00:24:56.640
I try to balance storytelling
and kind of social science

00:24:56.640 --> 00:24:58.410
research is that
I'm trying to find

00:24:58.410 --> 00:25:00.560
some kind of middle ground.

00:25:00.560 --> 00:25:03.010
I'm trying to find
an observation that

00:25:03.010 --> 00:25:06.340
is being made in the
literature or by academics

00:25:06.340 --> 00:25:08.440
and illustrated by
means of a story.

00:25:08.440 --> 00:25:11.970
So it's rare that the
story comes first.

00:25:11.970 --> 00:25:14.940
It's not that I hear something
cool and then hunt for data

00:25:14.940 --> 00:25:15.487
to fit that.

00:25:15.487 --> 00:25:16.570
It's the other way around.

00:25:16.570 --> 00:25:19.160
I look for an idea that's
been expressed in academia.

00:25:19.160 --> 00:25:28.880
And I say, well, how can I
make that story resonant,

00:25:28.880 --> 00:25:31.090
make that, sorry,
observation resonant?

00:25:31.090 --> 00:25:37.340
So you hunt for stories
that match this kind of idea

00:25:37.340 --> 00:25:42.990
that you feel has some
firepower behind it.

00:25:42.990 --> 00:25:46.870
But that said, it's a
necessarily imperfect process.

00:25:46.870 --> 00:25:49.170
All my books are
massively imperfect.

00:25:49.170 --> 00:25:52.790
I don't imagine that
anyone will ever

00:25:52.790 --> 00:25:55.032
agree with 100% of
the things in my book.

00:25:55.032 --> 00:25:56.740
I don't even want them
to agree with 100%

00:25:56.740 --> 00:25:58.640
of the things in the book.

00:25:58.640 --> 00:25:59.950
That's not what you want.

00:25:59.950 --> 00:26:02.541
You're not looking for converts.

00:26:02.541 --> 00:26:04.166
You want people to
start conversations.

00:26:07.700 --> 00:26:11.890
And writers who are looking
for converts are scary.

00:26:11.890 --> 00:26:13.730
I think what you're
looking for is

00:26:13.730 --> 00:26:17.380
you want people to
engage with the ideas.

